   <mods:abstract>Military movements. From Charleston. Most of the British force has been in
            summer quarters on Port Royal Island. Many of those troops have now gone to Georgia.
            Some troops that remain are in Beaufort and guarding important passes. The Continental
            troops number about 900, divided between Fort Moultrie, the city of Charleston and
            Sheldon. Unfortunately cannot protect the country from marauding Indians employed by the
            British. Colonel Parker and Major Jameson have passed through South Carolina and are now
            in Augusta. The troops under General Scott are only at half what they had expected. Has
            asked the General Assembly of the state for 4000 men, if not by volunteer than by
            drafting men. Fears that the enemy will receive reinforcements from New York before the
            Continental Army can add to their own numbers and attempt to subdue the southern states.
            Has heard from Havana that Spain has declared war on Great Britain. More reports of
            fighting in Georgia, between troops under Colonel Twiggs and Major Jameson and British
            troops under McGirt.</mods:abstract>
